# --- Inbound auth (tashtiot-apis-library >= v1.0.0) ---
# app/main.py builds the app with general_create_app(enable_auth=True) — that only installs
# the *capability*. The library's AuthMiddleware only actually protects every route (except
# /health, /metrics, /docs, /redoc, /openapi.json, /static, /.well-known, probes) once BOTH
# of these are true:
#   1) AUTH_ENABLED=true                     # master switch; unset/false = app boots open
#   2) exactly ONE verification-material source below is set
# These AUTH_* vars are read directly by the library's own settings, not by this app's
# global_conf.py — setting them here (or in devtools-definition's values.yaml env block for
# the real deployment) is enough, no code change needed.
# AUTH_ENABLED=true
#
# Real deployment: verify tokens issued by this platform's own Keycloak (rhbk), via OIDC
# discovery — this fetches /.well-known/openid-configuration at startup to find the JWKS URL:
# AUTH_OIDC_ISSUER=https://rhbk.devopstashtiot.page/realms/devtools
# AUTH_AUDIENCE=devops-api                   # must match the "devops-api-audience" client scope's audience mapper (see clusters-provision/clusters/rhbk)
#
# Local dev only — verify a self-signed token instead of hitting Keycloak at all:
#   1. pip install tashtiot-apis-library (already in requirements.txt), then run: gen-auth-material
#      This writes jwt_private.pem/jwt_public.pem and prints a non-expiring dev token.
#   2. AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY_PATH=jwt_public.pem
#   3. AUTH_REQUIRE_EXP=false                # the dev token has no exp claim
#   4. curl -H "Authorization: Bearer <printed token>" http://localhost:5000/...
#
# See this repo's top-level CLAUDE.md ("Inbound auth" section) for the full picture (why this
# exists, what it does and doesn't protect against, how to generate a real Keycloak
# client-credentials token).